body:
Annoyingly, if we want to do this for 0.21.0, we'll also likely have to bump our minimum required macOS from 10.12 to 10.14. 

You cannot use `std::get` with `std::variant` on macOS < 10.14, because Apples libc++ doesn't support the `std::bad_variant_access` exception. [Relevant comment](https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/pull/19183#discussion_r439794318) in #19183.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <variant>

int main() {
	std::variant<int, std::string> i, s;
	i = 42;
	s = "Hello";
	try {
		std::cout << std::get<int>(i) << "\n";
	} catch (const std::bad_variant_access&) {}
}
```

```bash
clang++ --version                                               
Apple clang version 11.0.3 (clang-1103.0.32.62)
Target: x86_64-apple-darwin19.5.0
```
```bash
clang++ -std=c++17 std_variant.cpp -O2 -mmacos-version-min=10.13
std_variant.cpp:9:21: error: 'get<int, int, std::__1::basic_string<char> >' is unavailable: introduced in macOS 10.14
                std::cout << std::get<int>(i) << "\n";
                                  ^
/Applications/Xcode.app/Contents/Developer/Toolchains/XcodeDefault.xctoolchain/usr/bin/../include/c++/v1/variant:1376:16: note: 'get<int, int, std::__1::basic_string<char> >' has been explicitly marked unavailable here
constexpr _Tp& get(variant<_Types...>& __v) {
               ^
std_variant.cpp:10:22: error: 'bad_variant_access' is unavailable: introduced in macOS 10.14
        } catch (const std::bad_variant_access&) {}
                            ^
/Applications/Xcode.app/Contents/Developer/Toolchains/XcodeDefault.xctoolchain/usr/bin/../include/c++/v1/variant:221:69: note: 'bad_variant_access' has been explicitly marked unavailable here
class _LIBCPP_EXCEPTION_ABI _LIBCPP_AVAILABILITY_BAD_VARIANT_ACCESS bad_variant_access : public exception {
                                                                    ^
2 errors generated.
```

While we could work around this in our own code, using `std::get_if`, this would still be a problem for 3rd-party dependencies. 

I've been testing Qt 5.15LTS (we'll have to enable c++17 in qt, and may upgrade to a newer version at the same time), and you can't enable `-std c++17`, while targeting a macOS deployment version < 10.14, configuring will fail. They are making use of `std::get` with `std::variant` throughout their cocoa code.

There is a similar problem with using `std::visit`. See my comment [here](https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/pull/19183#discussion_r439794419).
